<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-320-838  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 320 838.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  April 9 1990 n462 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Export reforms fall short.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer Industry representatives expressed some pleasure at theannounced relaxation of certain export controls, but say theadministration has not gone far enough.andP;  The US Department ofCommerce has recently been given the final authority over somelicenses that were issued by the Department of Defense, but thecomputer industry would like to see much more control shifted tothe DOC.andP;  DOC now controls licenses for computers running at54-Mbytes or less, a classification that would include some oldermainframes.andP;  DOC will also oversee computers running up to550-Mbytes that will be used in trade shows in Eastern Europe.andO;The computer industry would like to see many other restrictionsremoved, particularly those requirements for export to the NATOallies, Japan and Australia.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryGovernment RegulationExportInternational TradeUnited States. Department of CommerceLicensing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>